"We have all set our political institutions to the ability of humanity to self-govern, to the ability of each one of us to govern ourselves, to control ourselves, and to receive ourselves according to the Ten Commandments of God."

The man who drafted our Constitution left no doubt that we should govern ourselves according to the Ten Commandments of God. The congress holds Christianity as the established religion of this United States of America:

The process of drafting the first amendment has made clear the intention of the founders; Because before they adopted the final text, the First Amendment went through almost a dozen different iterations and in-depth discussions.

"We do not want in America what we had in the UK: we do not want a nation to lead the nation, we will not all be Catholics or Anglicans or any other denomination, we want God's principles, but we do not want a nation the nation rules. "

A fatwa is a non-binding legal opinion that can only be issued by a qualified lawyer (mufti) at the request of someone who can not understand religious guidelines. My life with the family as He. Entrepreneur was corrupted for Dubious Actions by vengeful officials of corrupt ISI, SBI, KFC, etc.
From 1982 to 1997, they played with my life as an SSI owner.

Cow in Hinduism:

Eating beef (Cow Mata) is allowed in Hinduism.
Rigveda (10/85/13) explains: "On the occasion of a girl's wedding, oxen and cows are slaughtered."
Rigveda (6/17/1) states that "Indra ate the meat of cow, calf, horse and buffalo".
Manusmriti (chapter 5 / verse 30) says, "It is not sinful to eat meat from edible animals, for Brahma created both the eaters and the edible."
Maharishi Yagyavalkya says in Shatpath Brahman (3/1/2/21): "I eat beef because it is very soft and delicious."
Apastamb Grihsutram (1/3/10) says: "The cow should be slaughtered on the arrival of a guest on the occasion of the 'Shraddha' of the ancestors and on the occasion of a wedding."
Vashistha Dharmasutra (11/34) writes, "When a Brahmin refuses to eat the flesh offered to him on the occasion of 'Shraddha' or worship, he goes to hell."

Dear Indian Express,
I'm sorry to write that your journalists are there to interpret events wrong and distorted display, just to make some sensational headlines. The news about the upcoming singer Nahid Afreen was prepared without proper research and investigation. It was very sad to see that your journalists do not even know the difference between fatwa and appeal.
A fatwa is a non-binding legal opinion that can only be issued by a qualified lawyer (mufti) at the request of someone who can not understand religious guidelines. The leaflet distributed as a fatwa is just a copy of a signed appeal from 46 men who believe in religious practices. The merit of the vocation can be discussed for many reasons and in many dimensions, but first and foremost an appeal can not be called a legal opinion (fatwa).
We expect an apology from you for such a mistake.

Margaux S Milk. The Treaty of Peace and Friendship between the United States of America and the Bey and the Subjects of Tripoli of Barbary, signed in Tripoli on November 4, 1796, Article 11 was established as a dispute between the English and Arabic translations of the treaty. Adams criticized the Roman Catholic Church's claim to universal authority, which could well form the basis for the wording of Article 11.

While it is true that Adams has signed the above contract, it should be noted that he also signed the Declaration of Independence and the Bill of Rights; Both are meant to misunderstand Adams's words. The fact that Congress has unanimously signed the treaty is absurd, if you accept the whole translation theme.

John Adams was both a devout Christian and an independent thinker. In a letter to Benjamin Rush, Adams attributed to the religion the success of his ancestors since their migration to the New World in the 1630s. He also believed that regular worship was conducive to the moral sense of man. In 1796 Adams condemned the deistic critique of Thomas Paine's political opponent of Christianity in the age of reason: "The Christian religion is above all the religion that reigned or existed in ancient or modern times, the religion of wisdom, virtue, justice and humanity, let the Black Paine say what he wants. "

In view of Adam's Christianity, translations from English into Arabic are very unlikely to be transcribed correctly. It is far more plausible that he rejected the claims of "universal authority" proclaimed by the Roman Catholic Church as anything that removed the basis of the Christian religion.

Adams twice served as vice president under President George Washington. The words of our esteemed first president in his farewell address dispute any idea that this United States of America is not founded on the Christian religion; "And let us dare with caution the assumption that morality can be sustained without religion, whatever may be conceded to the influence of refined education on the heads of the peculiar structure, reason and experience forbid us to expect the national Morality under exclusion of the religious principle. "

The words of James Madison, the father of our Constitution, clearly contradict the notion that America is not a Christian nation; "We have all set our political institutions to the ability of humanity to self-govern, to the ability of each one of us to govern ourselves, to control ourselves, and to receive ourselves according to the Ten Commandments of God."

Dear Indian Express,
I'm sorry to write that your journalists are there to interpret events wrong and distorted display, just to make some sensational headlines. The news about the upcoming singer Nahid Afreen was prepared without proper research and investigation. It was very sad to see that your journalists do not even know the difference between fatwa and appeal.
A fatwa is a non-binding legal opinion that can only be issued by a qualified lawyer (mufti) at the request of someone who can not understand religious guidelines. The leaflet distributed as a fatwa is just a copy of a signed appeal from 46 men who believe in religious practices. The merit of the vocation can be discussed for many reasons and in many dimensions, but first and foremost an appeal can not be called a legal opinion (fatwa).
We expect an apology from you for such a mistake

Rigveda (10/85/13) explains: "On the occasion of a girl's wedding, oxen and cows are slaughtered."
Rigveda (6/17/1) states that "Indra ate the meat of cow, calf, horse and buffalo".
Manusmriti (chapter 5 / verse 30) says, "It is not sinful to eat meat from edible animals, for Brahma created both the eaters and the edible."
Maharishi Yagyavalkya says in Shatpath Brahman (3/1/2/21): "I eat beef because it is very soft and delicious."
Apastamb Grihsutram (1/3/10) says: "The cow should be slaughtered on the arrival of a guest on the occasion of the 'Shraddha' of the ancestors and on the occasion of a wedding."
Vashistha Dharmasutra (11/34) writes, "When a Brahmin refuses to eat the flesh offered to him on the occasion of 'Shraddha' or worship, he goes to hell."

Dear Indian Express,
I'm sorry to write that your journalists are there to interpret events wrong and distorted display, just to make some sensational headlines. The news about the upcoming singer Nahid Afreen was prepared without proper research and investigation. It was very sad to see that your journalists do not even know the difference between fatwa and appeal.
A fatwa is a non-binding legal opinion that can only be issued by a qualified lawyer (mufti) at the request of someone who can not understand religious guidelines. The leaflet distributed as a fatwa is just a copy of a signed appeal from 46 men who believe in religious practices. The merit of the vocation can be discussed for many reasons and in many dimensions, but first and foremost an appeal can not be called a legal opinion (fatwa).

http://indianexpress.com/article/india/fatwa-issued-against-reality-singing-star-nahid-afrin-by-42-clerics-4569825/

Dear Indian Express,
I'm sorry to write that your journalists are there to interpret events wrong and distorted display, just to make some sensational headlines. The news about the upcoming singer Nahid Afreen was prepared without proper research and investigation. It was very sad to see that your journalists do not even know the difference between fatwa and appeal.
A fatwa is a non-binding legal opinion that can only be issued by a qualified lawyer (mufti) at the request of someone who can not understand religious guidelines. The leaflet distributed as a fatwa is just a copy of a signed appeal from 46 men who believe in religious practices. The merit of the vocation can be discussed for many reasons and in many dimensions, but first and foremost an appeal can not be called a legal opinion (fatwa).
We expect an apology from you for such a mistake.

Conversions that take place in unrecognized centers in the state could be much higher, fear government officials who for obvious reasons did not want to be named. The report states that nearly half of those who convert to Islam are women and that the majority of these women (76%) are under the age of 35. Of the converts, 4,719 were Hindus and the remaining 1,074 were mostly Christians. The conversions took place in Tharbiyathul Islam Sabha in Kozhikode and Monunsthil Islam Sabha in Ponnani, two traditional religious institutions in the state, which were authorized to convert people from other religions to Islam. The police report, which was created in connection with the conversion of Nimisha aka Fathima, who is currently missing along with 20 others from the state and is believed to have joined the Islamic State, says a detailed investigation is needed to Check if these conversions were under pressure were enticements involved or were voluntary. Dr. Dorhoi attended the reception of the F√©d√©ration Internationale de l'Automobile (FIA) at the Marriott Marquis in Washington DC on Monday, January 11, 2016. Previously, she spent 7 years funding road rehabilitation worldwide. Dr. Dorhoi also works on the financing and management of risks in Formula 1 within the framework of different financing requirements.

Many thanks to the F√©d√©ration Internationale de l'Automobile Foundation (FIA) for preparing and publishing progress on the implementation of the United Nations Road Safety in 2015 objectives. The report was prepared by the World Health Organization.

The event also featured the book "Goals for Change, Partners for Action" of the 2015 Annual Report of the F√©d√©ration Internationale de l'Automobile Foundation (FIA).

The report welcomes the UN Decade of Road Safety and the UN Sustainable Development Goals. More specifically, the Energy Goals for Development have been translated into a Global Fuel Economy Initiative, in which the Foundation supports governments in developing global and regional programs to find evidence of effectiveness at national and city level and donors to support national policies and policies initiatives.

In the United States, about 40% of traffic-related deaths have been reduced in recent years. The United Nations 2020 Millennium Development Goals on Road Safety are designed to reduce road fatalities by 50% compared to today's levels.

For Dr. Dorhoi's association with the F√©d√©ration Internationale de l'Automobile Foundation (FIA) is blessed by her long-standing devotion to the cause of Ayrton Senna. http://indianexpress.com/article/india/fatwa-issued-against-reality-singing-star-nahid-afrin-by-42-clerics-4569825/

Dear Indian Express,
I'm sorry to write that your journalists are there to interpret events wrong and distorted display, just to make some sensational headlines. The news about the upcoming singer Nahid Afreen was prepared without proper research and investigation. It was very sad to see that your journalists do not even know the difference between fatwa and appeal.
A fatwa is a non-binding legal opinion that can only be issued by a qualified lawyer (mufti) at the request of someone who can not understand religious guidelines. The leaflet distributed as a fatwa is just a copy of a signed appeal from 46 men who believe in religious practices. The merit of the vocation can be discussed for many reasons and in many dimensions, but first and foremost an appeal can not be called a legal opinion (fatwa).
We expect an apology from you for such a mistake

Top 10 tricks with which the media control the masses:

1. Project "Everything is alright" in standard mode - even if this is not the case - and so lull people into complacency. (Buffer routine "news", sports, celebrity gossip, science, etc.). This technique is used by shepherds who keep sheep for slaughter.

2. emphasis on individual identity (nationality, religion, state, etc.) to ensure a subconscious separation (the policy of sharing and governing).

3. Lead the "voice of the poor" / "power of protest" etc., although these do not exist. This deceives people to "think" that they are in control.

4. Stage events ('astro turfing', 'shills', 'fake witnesses', 'crisis actors' etc.) to either create 'mass movements', create paranoia or extreme fear or distract masses from real problems.

5. Use sports, celebrities and gossip, etc., to distract from real problems (and to shape public opinion).

6. Play important support role for big sponsored false flag events, hoaxes, etc. (for wars, laws, create fear, distract, etc.) Many of your favorite news anchors and journalists are indeed establishment (intelligence) officers.

7th Portra government as a victim of a crime (fraud, attack, etc.), so that the group would later protest against draconian laws against itself.

8. Producing extreme anxiety through exaggerated claims about illness, hostile power, terrorism, etc. (eg to support wars, desensitize or divide people)

9. "Media Black Out", or reporting with malice, (stereotyping or demonization) - the most common control technique.

10. Finally, and most secretly, the media are owned by a handful of companies and suppress other sources of information. The media form the "matrix" - a network of illusions to deceive the masses, and together with "politics" are both secretly owned by banking families.

Next time, when your favorite media is breaking news, ask yourself, is this true, or is this your latest Shill / Hoax / False-Flag operation?

Dear Indian Express,
I'm sorry to write that your journalists are there to interpret events wrong and distorted display, just to make some sensational headlines. The news about the upcoming singer Nahid Afreen was prepared without proper research and investigation. It was very sad to see that your journalists do not even know the difference between fatwa and appeal.
A fatwa is a non-binding legal opinion that can only be issued by a qualified lawyer (mufti) at the request of someone who can not understand religious guidelines. The leaflet distributed as a fatwa is just a copy of a signed appeal from 46 men who believe in religious practices. The merit of the vocation can be discussed for many reasons and in many dimensions, but first and foremost an appeal can not be called a legal opinion (fatwa).
We expect an apology from you for such a mistake

I remember these fateful days when I was studying in Delhi at school. For the first time in my life, I felt like a minority in India. It is very sad that even 27 years after the massacre of innocent Sikhs that took place between November 1 and 3, 1984, after Indira's death, no justice has been done to the victims of these vile GENOCIDE or their perpetrators (mainly local MLAs & their goons ) were tried or put to book. According to the BBC, within 4 days 20,000 SIKHS were massacred in broad daylight throughout India and the state police (like the Delhi police) did nothing to stop this brutal ETHNIC CLEANING. They just stood there like silent spectators watching the gruesome spectacle set in motion and in some cases even conspiring with the perpetrators. HER ELDER MINISTERS SUCH AS JAGDISH TYTLER & KAMAL NATH ARE CONNECTED IN THIS GENOCIDE. During this time, Sikhs were burned alive in front of their families, killed with iron bars and their wives raped and their places of worship ravished. For the Sikh community it was like another HOLOCAUST. There were more victims in government-controlled states (obviously). The state police became deaf to the repeated requests of the affected Sikh families for protection, as the angry mobs continued their gruesome deed in one Sikh location after another. In many Sikh communities, entire Sikh communities were wiped out. There are photos of people laughing as they beat the Sikhs to death.

I was 13 years old in Delhi when this carnage took place. I have very vivid and painful memories of those days. I am also a Sikh but luckily we were safe as our residence was in the Cantonment of Delhi, which was a safe area. Had I been in an unsafe area, I would have met the same fate. My father picked me and my sister from our school bus on October 31, 1984, as we had to walk a short distance to our house. I remember that between November 1 and 4, 1984, the entire city was under curfew and I did not go to school for a month. An eerie silence of death permeated the whole city. For the first time, I felt that I was a minority person living in a country governed by the majority society. I remember seeing black fumes coming out of nearby Janakpuri on November 1st. We had to install security guards in front of our house for a month before things calmed down, although there were threats that a mob would come to us.

DELAYED JUSTICE IS DENIED JUSTICE. comment_text:
Cow in Hinduism:

Eating beef (Cow Mata) is allowed in Hinduism.
Rigveda (10/85/13) explains: "On the occasion of a girl's wedding, oxen and cows are slaughtered."
Rigveda (6/17/1) states that "Indra ate the meat of cow, calf, horse and buffalo".
Manusmriti (chapter 5 / verse 30) says, "It is not sinful to eat meat from edible animals, for Brahma created both the eaters and the edible."
Maharishi Yagyavalkya says in Shatpath Brahman (3/1/2/21): "I eat beef because it is very soft and delicious."
Apastamb Grihsutram (1/3/10) says: "The cow should be slaughtered on the arrival of a guest on the occasion of the 'Shraddha' of the ancestors and on the occasion of a wedding."
Vashistha Dharmasutra (11/34) writes, "When a Brahmin refuses to eat the flesh offered to him on the occasion of 'Shraddha' or worship, he goes to hell."

comment_text:
Dear Indian Express,
I'm sorry to write that your journalists are there to interpret events wrong and distorted display, just to make some sensational headlines. The news about the upcoming singer Nahid Afreen was prepared without proper research and investigation. It was very sad to see that your journalists do not even know the difference between fatwa and appeal.

comment_text:
http://indianexpress.com/article/india/fatwa-issued-against-reality-singing-star-nahid-afrin-by-42-clerics-4569825/

Dear Indian Express,
I'm sorry to write that your journalists are there to interpret events wrong and distorted display, just to make some sensational headlines. The news about the upcoming singer Nahid Afreen was prepared without proper research and investigation. It was very sad to see that your journalists do not even know the difference between fatwa and appeal.
A fatwa is a non-binding legal opinion that can only be issued by a qualified lawyer (mufti) at the request of someone who can not understand religious guidelines. The leaflet distributed as a fatwa is just a copy of a signed appeal from 46 men who believe in religious practices. The merit of the vocation can be discussed for many reasons and in many dimensions, but first and foremost an appeal can not be called a legal opinion (fatwa).
We expect an apology from you for such a mistake.

comment_text:
http://indianexpress.com/.../fatwa-issued-against.../

Dear Indian Express,
I'm sorry to write that your journalists are there to interpret events wrong and distorted display, just to make some sensational headlines. The news about the upcoming singer Nahid Afreen was prepared without proper research and investigation. It was very sad to see that your journalists do not even know the difference between fatwa and appeal.
A fatwa is a non-binding legal opinion that can only be issued by a qualified lawyer (mufti) at the request of someone who can not understand religious guidelines. The leaflet distributed as a fatwa is just a copy of a signed appeal from 46 men who believe in religious practices. The merit of the vocation can be discussed for many reasons and in many dimensions, but first and foremost an appeal can not be called a legal opinion (fatwa).
We expect an apology from you for such a mistake

comment_text:
When we travel abroad in other countries, road fines are huge, which makes people take driving as a responsible and careful matter. Drunk driving is 6 months in prison in some countries.

In India, we change the lanes without showing, drive drunk, after the stop line at red signal and jump, without thinking twice about the serious consequences. Absence of emergency lanes on roads. People do not give place to ambulances and other rescue vehicles. I also lost my mother in the ambulance because few people had more important places and blocked our way. Believe me, your driving perspective would change completely if you are in such a situation.

Therefore, I fully support the Government's decision to impose fines in line with global standards, and I hope that all transport offenders get what they actually deserve.

comment_text:
Cow in Hinduism:

Eating beef (Cow Mata) is allowed in Hinduism.
Rigveda (10/85/13) explains: "On the occasion of a girl's wedding, oxen and cows are slaughtered."
Rigveda (6/17/1) states that "Indra ate the meat of cow, calf, horse and buffalo".
Manusmriti (chapter 5 / verse 30) says, "It is not sinful to eat meat from edible animals, for Brahma created both the eaters and the edible."
Maharishi Yagyavalkya says in Shatpath Brahman (3/1/2/21): "I eat beef because it is very soft and delicious."
Apastamb Grihsutram (1/3/10) says: "The cow should be slaughtered on the arrival of a guest on the occasion of the 'Shraddha' of the ancestors and on the occasion of a wedding."
Vashistha Dharmasutra (11/34) writes, "When a Brahmin refuses to eat the flesh offered to him on the occasion of 'Shraddha' or worship, he goes to hell."

Dear Indian Express,
I'm sorry to write that your journalists are there to interpret events wrong and distorted display, just to make some sensational headlines. The news about the upcoming singer Nahid Afreen was prepared without proper research and investigation. It was very sad to see that your journalists do not even know the difference between fatwa and appeal.
A fatwa is a non-binding legal opinion that can only be issued by a qualified lawyer (mufti) at the request of someone who can not understand religious guidelines. The leaflet distributed as a fatwa is just a copy of a signed appeal from 46 men who believe in religious practices. The merit of the vocation can be discussed for many reasons and in many dimensions, but first and foremost an appeal can not be called a legal opinion (fatwa).
We expect an apology from you for such a mistake

Tiger: If you have problems with Muslim Azan, you also need to have problems with Hindu Aarti. Both cause noise pollution.

Agniverer: There are differences.

How many times have you woken up in mosques at 4:30 am due to the noise of Azan? 365 times a year (if you live within 5 km of a mosque).

Zero vs 365 does it all.

Even if the Aarti loudspeaker near you starts at 4:30 am at full volume, you can just go to the priest and he will reduce it. Just try a Moulvi in ‚Äã‚Äãa mosque and see if you come back in one piece.

Tiger: Huh, and what about your Ganesh Yatra, Hanuman Yatra? Do not they make noise? Stop her.

Tiger: At least 10 days.

Tiger:

Agniverer: Why quiet? Let me help you. 365 * 5 = 1825. And then there are rallies, bike stunts, processions, etc. on the Prophet's B'day, Eid, and Muharram.

So it's 10 against 1825+. Are 10 and 1825 the same?

Tiger: Wrong is wrong. There is no greater or less wrong.

Agniverer: Okay, then your 34/36/38 waist size is also wrong. Come to us before commenting on our concerns about Azan.

Tiger: How can you compare my personal fitness problem with a problem of 20% minorities?

Tiger:

Agniverer: Why quiet?

And finally, there is a big difference. There is a strong correlation between the density of Azan and terror. Find the places on earth where

1. Azan is maximum (let's call it # 1)
2. Aarti is maximum (let's call it 2nd place)

This is the ultimate litmus test where noise is dangerous and harmless.

Tiger:

Agniverer: Why quiet?

Tiger: Who are you man?

Agniverer: A proud Hindu. A proud idol worshiper. A proud jihadi hater. A proud Indian. Agniverer is the name.

* Trump's first day at the Oval Office after being elected president. *

First briefing of the CIA, Pentagon, FBI:

Trump: We have to destroy the IS immediately. No delays.

CIA: We can not do that, sir. We have created them together with Turkey, Saudi Arabia, Qatar and others.

Trump: The Democrats created them.

CIA: We created ISIS, sir. You need them, otherwise you would lose financing from the natural gas lobby.

Trump: Stop financing Pakistan. Let India handle them.

CIA: We can not do that.

Trump: Why is that?

CIA: India will cut off Balochistan from Pak.

Trump: I do not care.

CIA: India will have peace in Kashmir. They will stop buying our weapons. You will become a superpower. We have to finance Pakistan to keep India busy in Kashmir.

Trump: But you have to destroy the Taliban.

CIA: Sir, we can not do that. We created the Taliban to keep Russia at bay in the 1980s. Now they keep Pakistan busy and away from their nuclear bombs.

Trump: We have to destroy terrorist regimes in the Middle East. Let's start with the Saudis.

Pentagon: Sir, we can not do that. We created these regimes because we wanted their oil. We can not have democracy there, otherwise their people will get that oil - and we can not let their people own it.

Trump: Then let's invade Iran.

Pentagon: We can not, sir.

Trump: Why not?

CIA: We're talking to you, sir.

Trump: What? Why?

CIA: We want our stealth drones back. If we attack them, Russia will wipe us out like our buddy ISIS in Syria. We also need Iran to keep Israel at bay.

Trump: Then let's invade Iraq again.

CIA: Sir, our friends (ISIS) already occupy 1/3 of Iraq.

Trump: Why not all Iraq?

CIA: We need the Shiite government in Iraq to keep the IS at bay.

Trump: I forbid Muslims to enter the US.

FBI: We can not do that.

Trump: Why not?

FBI: Then our own population will become fearless.

Trump: I'm deporting all illegal immigrants south of the border.

Border Patrol: You can not do that, sir.

Trump: Why not?

Border patrol: When they are gone, who will build the wall?

Trump: I ban H1B visas.

comment_text:
Kevin Gaskin. You are welcome to search the Bill of Rights, the US Constitution, and the Declaration of Independence, but you will find nothing about the "separation of church and state" in one of them.

Thomas Jefferson wrote a letter to the Danbury Baptist Association in 1802 to answer a letter from them asking why he would not announce national Lenten and Thanksgiving holidays, as Washington and Adams had done before him. The letter contains the phrase "wall of separation between church and state" that led to the erroneous "shorthand" for the Establishment Clause (US Constitution, Bill of Rights, Amendment I, Article III) that we use today.

"Why do I have religious freedom ...?" The answer lay in the congressional papers relating to our constitution, as we know it today. The process of drafting the first amendment has made clear the intention of the founders; Because before they adopted the final text, the First Amendment went through almost a dozen different iterations and in-depth discussions.

"We do not want in America what we had in the UK: we do not want a nation to lead the nation, we will not all be Catholics or Anglicans or any other denomination, we want God's principles, but we do not want a nation the nation rules. "

This intention was well understood as evidence by court judgments under the First Amendment. In 1799, the court stated, "According to our form of government, the Christian religion is the established religion, and all the sects and denominations of Christians are equal."

It is important to realize that our founding fathers sought to gain "religious freedom" because of the oppressive authority of the Roman Catholic Church. It was not just Great Britain, but the largest part of Europe that came under the authority of Roman Catholicism. Our founding fathers began to recognize the many denominations of Christianity. In addition, they intended to recognize each denomination as equivalent, as opposed to granting control by any denomination. Herein lies the misinterpretation of the reckless "shorthand," known as "separation of church and state."

A more accurate statement is likely to be "Separation of church and state denominations". Such an interpretation is clear from the papers of Congress regarding the statement "We do not want what we had in the UK in America: we do not want a denomination that leads the nation, we will not all be Catholics or Anglicans or any other denomination We want God's principles, but we do not want a nation to rule the nation. "

As for the statement, "Most of our founding fathers were agnostic," that's simply not true. It is a general statement made by those who oppose religion in general. Yes, at that time there were agnostics, but they were not nearly as widespread as claimed. Thomas Paine was an Anglo-American political activist, philosopher, political theorist and revolutionary. Although he is considered one of our founding fathers, he was shunned because of his well-known agnostic convictions.

John Adams is falsely accused of being an agnostic. But here is a quote from President Adams regarding Thomas Paine; "The Christian religion is above all the religions that ever ruled or existed, the religion of wisdom, virtue, equality and humanity. Let Black King Paine say what he wants." I believe you will agree with his words regarding Mr. Paine are more than sufficient to dispel claims of his agnostic convictions.

Q1) Are GDP data misused?

- Yes they are. They are not accurate. They are abused to promote a lie.

Q2) Can you prove that GDP data is misused?

- By January 2015, the Indian economy had been experiencing valuable growth since the mid-1980s. And then the magic happened. The Central Statistical Office (CSO) has changed the calculation of GDP, stating that this is necessary in the light of global practices. As a result, India overtook China and became the fastest growing economy. In 2013-2014, our economy grew 6.9% instead of 4.7% as the CSO data showed earlier. Arvind Subramanian, the country's top economic advisor, said, "I'm confused about the new GDP growth figures." The revised figures show that GDP growth in 2012-2013 increased from 4.7% to 5.1% and for 2013-2013. From 5% to 6.9% in 2014. This means an acceleration in GDP growth of 1.9 percentage points in 2013-2014, simply by comparing the new numbers over time. "These figures, in particular the acceleration in 2013- 2014, are at odds with other macroeconomic features "Almost every economist working inside or outside the government (including Mr. Raghuram Rajan) questioned GDP figures as land conditions reflected a completely different picture. Figures seemed completely at odds with other economic indicators According to R Nagraj, an independent member of the subcommittee, who is investigating the new methodology for estimating production The version adopted by the Central Stability Organization was significantly different from the report finalized by the Subcommittee in September 2014.

Q3) What about the latest GDP data released after demonetization?

- You are also deceived. While the performance of a few sectors was better than in previous quarters, the huge improvement in private consumption (almost doubled) seems very doubtful given the cash crunch during demonetization. It seems that the CSO was unable to reproduce the demonetisation effect in its data. Both the government and the RBI have said (as well as few of their judicious critics) that the effects of demonetization can be replicated over a longer period of time. The CSO also revised the Q3 estimates for 2015/16 by 0.3 percentage points to 6.9% from 7.2% previously, leading to a significant improvement in the third quarter 2016/17 figures. For those who find it unsurprising, the CSO revised the 2015-16 UP Q1 and Q2 estimates. This downward revision in the third quarter of 2015-16 has helped to limit the effect of demonetization in numbers.

Q4) I can not understand anything. Why?

- You will not get it. You are neither a statistician nor an economist. Every time reports and statements like these emerge, they push themselves a little on the internet beyond Facebook and Twitter and read about basic things and what experts have to say about them.

comment_text:
Cow in Hinduism:

Eating beef (Cow Mata) is allowed in Hinduism.
Rigveda (10/85/13) explains: "On the occasion of a girl's wedding, oxen and cows are slaughtered."
Rigveda (6/17/1) states that "Indra ate the meat of cow, calf, horse and buffalo".
Manusmriti (chapter 5 / verse 30) says, "It is not sinful to eat meat from edible animals, for Brahma created both the eaters and the edible."
Maharishi Yagyavalkya says in Shatpath Brahman (3/1/2/21): "I eat beef because it is very soft and delicious."
Apastamb Grihsutram (1/3/10) says: "The cow should be slaughtered on the arrival of a guest on the occasion of the 'Shraddha' of the ancestors and on the occasion of a wedding."
Vashistha Dharmasutra (11/34) writes, "When a Brahmin refuses to eat the flesh offered to him on the occasion of 'Shraddha' or worship, he goes to hell."

Dear Indian Express,
I'm sorry to write that your journalists are there to interpret events wrong and distorted display, just to make some sensational headlines. The news about the upcoming singer Nahid Afreen was prepared without proper research and investigation. It was very sad to see that your journalists do not even know the difference between fatwa and appeal.
A fatwa is a non-binding legal opinion that can only be issued by a qualified lawyer (mufti) at the request of someone who can not understand religious guidelines. The leaflet distributed as a fatwa is just a copy of a signed appeal from 46 men who believe in religious practices. The merit of the vocation can be discussed for many reasons and in many dimensions, but first and foremost an appeal can not be called a legal opinion (fatwa).
We expect an apology from you for such a mistake
